	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">kevtris wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">infiniteneslives wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">TmEE wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">NES does not have 2.54mm contact centers, there is going to be some major lineup problems with those connectors...</div><br /><br />?<br /><br />The contacts are 0.100" (2.54 mm) pitch as I measure with my calipers anyways.  Pitch being the start of one pin to the start of the next.<br /><br />I ordered a pair of them this morning so we'll see how it goes.  Worst case I'll return them.</div><br /><br />They are NOT .1"  they are 2.5mm apart.  This is slightly smaller;  it causes an error buildup over several pins.  .1" connectors might work but will probably be finicky.</div>
<br />
<br />Well they showed up today and I'm pretty happy with them so far.
<br />
<br />I haven't put anything together yet, but I did some quick continuity checks with my multimeter and I couldn't cause any connection problems testing it out with a board removed from it's case.
<br />
<br />There is only 0.019" free play side to side with the board in the connector and I could get anything to loose contact or short between pins.  I know there may be a technical difference in exact pitch, but they work perfectly together.
<br />
<br />TmEE must have gotten a different one than this, perhaps more free play than mine?
<br />
<br />I've done some placement with the NES and I think I've found a good solution using some protoboard.  There is a slight clearance issue that can easily be fix or avoided without much affect.
<br />
<br />I'll post it up with pictures when I get something completed in the next day or two.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
